<br>
It's simple, yes pets can get snared, feared, rooted, and mezzed, so you gotta make sure you can't.  Have your MR as high as you can get it, it's the most important resist, followed by PR, DR, and then FR and CR.  Also at level 34 I believe or maybe 39 you can summon a non lore dagger with +5 MR on it.  Give two to your pet and watch, on a pet 10 MR is a lot.<br>
<br>
Your pet just got snared?  Your pet just got rooted?  Not the end of the world.  If your opponent is a melee, keep moving at all times and keep your pet between yourself and your opponent and maybe try to get off a spell or two.  Stick close to your pet and the meleer can't get close without taking a couple hits from the pet.  If your opponent is a SK, and he DoTs you, get as close to your pet as you can and pumice them off.  Also try to keep your phantom armor line up as it will help.<br>
<br>
If your opponent is a caster, same advice.  Keep your pet between you and your enemy but if he starts to cast a spell, back up out of range of his spell and fire a bolt off at him.  When he moves around your pet to get closer to you move to where your pet is still between you and the caster.  Root should wear off fast and if your pet has been snared, it'll still be moving and will get a couple hits here and there and your bolts will take the caster down a great deal of hitpoints.<br>
<br>
Feared pet?  Again, not the end of the world, when your pet runs, stay near it.  Fear won't last forever and as soon as your pet's fear spell comes off, it's right back on the caster and you can get off a nuke or two before it begins to nuke again.<br>
<br>
Mezzed pet?  Ok this sucks so make sure your MR is high and nuke the chanter or you could try to pumice your pet but I don't recommend that.  Mez won't last forever and once it breaks, your pet will be back after the chanter.  With the new bonus to the tashania line in pvp, enchanters are brutal so be careful.<br>
<br>
Remember to stick close to your pet at all times and use bolts from outside normal casting range.  Bolt spells are the biggest advantage to a disadvantaged pvp class.  I wish mages got another form of escape or a rune type spell but we don't so we have to make due with what we have. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uonyxrosevalsharess.showPublicProfile?language=EN>OnyxroseValSharess</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 30<br> <font color=#333333>(6/25/01 2:33:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=47.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Tips for pvping with a mage</span><hr size=1> I was in South Karanas hunting you-know-who (starts with Q, ends in -where-the-heck-is-he) when I was attacked by a Ranger.<br>
<br>
The Ranger snared me, then ran off with my pet trailing him...  so I sat down and quick-memorized a new spell...  Sure enough, he ran off a short distance, and snared my pet, with the idea that he could come back and melee me to death with no defense.<br>
<br>
It was around that point that I cast Summon Companion, and back popped my pet to my side.  A few quick Cancel Magics, and my pet was back running at full speed.  By the time the Ranger ran back to me, he was quite supprised to see my pet...<br>
<br>
